147 FMT_BEGIN_NAMESPACE
148 namespace internal {
149 // Avoid Clang with Microsoft CodeGen's -Wunknown-pragmas warning.
150 #ifndef __clang__
151 #pragma intrinsic(_BitScanReverse)
152 #endif
153  inline uint32_t clz(uint32_t x)
154  {
155  unsigned long r = 0;
156  _BitScanReverse(&r, x);
157 
158  assert(x != 0);
159  // Static analysis complains about using uninitialized data
160  // "r", but the only way that can happen is if "x" is 0,
161  // which the callers guarantee to not happen.
162 #pragma warning(suppress : 6102)
163  return 31 - r;
164  }
165 #define FMT_BUILTIN_CLZ(n) fmt::internal::clz(n)
166 
167 #if defined(_WIN64) && !defined(__clang__)
168 #pragma intrinsic(_BitScanReverse64)
169 #endif
170 
171  inline uint32_t clzll(uint64_t x)
172  {
173  unsigned long r = 0;
174 #ifdef _WIN64
175  _BitScanReverse64(&r, x);
176 #else
177  // Scan the high 32 bits.
178  if (_BitScanReverse(&r, static_cast<uint32_t>(x >> 32)))
179  return 63 - (r + 32);
180 
181  // Scan the low 32 bits.
182  _BitScanReverse(&r, static_cast<uint32_t>(x));
183 #endif
184 
185  assert(x != 0);
186  // Static analysis complains about using uninitialized data
187  // "r", but the only way that can happen is if "x" is 0,
188  // which the callers guarantee to not happen.
189 #pragma warning(suppress : 6102)
190  return 63 - r;
191  }
192 #define FMT_BUILTIN_CLZLL(n) fmt::internal::clzll(n)
193 } // namespace internal
194 FMT_END_NAMESPACE
195 #endif

211  // An equivalent of `*reinterpret_cast<Dest*>(&source)` that doesn't produce
212  // undefined behavior (e.g. due to type aliasing).
213  // Example: uint64_t d = bit_cast<uint64_t>(2.718);
214  template <typename Dest, typename Source> inline Dest bit_cast(const Source &source)
215  {
216  static_assert(sizeof(Dest) == sizeof(Source), "size mismatch");
217  Dest dest;
218  std::memcpy(&dest, &source, sizeof(dest));
219  return dest;
220  }

225  // Detect the iterator category of *any* given type in a SFINAE-friendly way.
226  // Unfortunately, older implementations of std::iterator_traits are not safe
227  // for use in a SFINAE-context.
228  template <typename It, typename Enable = void> struct iterator_category : std::false_type
229  {
230  };

233  {
234  using type = std::random_access_iterator_tag;
235  };

238  {

242  // Detect if *any* given type models the OutputIterator concept.
243  template <typename It> class is_output_iterator
244  {
245  // Check for mutability because all iterator categories derived from
246  // std::input_iterator_tag *may* also meet the requirements of an
247  // OutputIterator, thereby falling into the category of 'mutable iterators'
248  // [iterator.requirements.general] clause 4. The compiler reveals this
249  // property only at the point of *actually dereferencing* the iterator!
250  template <typename U> static decltype(*(std::declval<U>())) test(std::input_iterator_tag);
251  template <typename U> static char & test(std::output_iterator_tag);
252  template <typename U> static const char & test(...);
253 
254  using type = decltype(test<It>(typename iterator_category<It>::type{}));
255 
256  public:
257  static const bool value = !std::is_const<remove_reference_t<type>>::value;
258  };

288  // An output iterator that counts the number of objects written to it and
289  // discards them.
290  template <typename T> class counting_iterator
291  {
292  private:
293  std::size_t count_;
294  mutable T blackhole_;
295 
296  public:
297  using iterator_category = std::output_iterator_tag;
298  using value_type = T;
299  using difference_type = std::ptrdiff_t;
300  using pointer = T *;
301  using reference = T &;
302  using _Unchecked_type = counting_iterator; // Mark iterator as checked.
303 
304  counting_iterator() : count_(0) {}
305 
306  std::size_t count() const { return count_; }
307 
308  counting_iterator &operator++()
309  {
310  ++count_;
311  return *this;
312  }
313 
314  counting_iterator operator++(int)
315  {
316  auto it = *this;
317  ++*this;
318  return it;
319  }
320 
321  T &operator*() const { return blackhole_; }

335  public:
336  using iterator_category = std::output_iterator_tag;
337  using difference_type = void;

339  using reference = void;

346  // An output iterator that truncates the output and counts the number of objects
347  // written to it.
348  template <typename OutputIt,
349  typename Enable =
350  typename std::is_void<typename std::iterator_traits<OutputIt>::value_type>::type>
351  class truncating_iterator;
352 
353  template <typename OutputIt>
354  class truncating_iterator<OutputIt, std::false_type> : public truncating_iterator_base<OutputIt>
355  {
356  using traits = std::iterator_traits<OutputIt>;
357 
358  mutable typename traits::value_type blackhole_;
359 
360  public:
361  using value_type = typename traits::value_type;
362 
363  truncating_iterator(OutputIt out, std::size_t limit)
364  : truncating_iterator_base<OutputIt>(out, limit)
365  {
366  }
367 
368  truncating_iterator &operator++()
369  {
370  if (this->count_++ < this->limit_)
371  ++this->out_;
372  return *this;
373  }
374 
375  truncating_iterator operator++(int)
376  {
377  auto it = *this;
378  ++*this;
379  return it;
380  }
381 
382  value_type &operator*() const { return this->count_ < this->limit_ ? *this->out_ : blackhole_; }
383  };
384 
385  template <typename OutputIt>
386  class truncating_iterator<OutputIt, std::true_type> : public truncating_iterator_base<OutputIt>
387  {
388  public:
389  using value_type = typename OutputIt::container_type::value_type;
390 
391  truncating_iterator(OutputIt out, std::size_t limit)
392  : truncating_iterator_base<OutputIt>(out, limit)
393  {
394  }
395 
396  truncating_iterator &operator=(value_type val)
397  {
398  if (this->count_++ < this->limit_)
399  this->out_ = val;
400  return *this;
401  }
402 
403  truncating_iterator &operator++() { return *this; }
404  truncating_iterator &operator++(int) { return *this; }
405  truncating_iterator &operator*() { return *this; }

441  // Counts the number of code points in a UTF-8 string.
442  inline size_t count_code_points(basic_string_view<char8_t> s)
443  {
444  const char8_t *data = s.data();
445  size_t num_code_points = 0;
446  for (size_t i = 0, size = s.size(); i != size; ++i) {
447  if ((data[i] & 0xc0) != 0x80)
448  ++num_code_points;
449  }
450  return num_code_points;
451  }

483  template <typename T>
484  template <typename U>
485  void buffer<T>::append(const U *p_begin, const U *p_end)
486  {
487  std::size_t new_size = size_ + to_unsigned(p_end - p_begin);
488  reserve(new_size);
489  std::uninitialized_copy(p_begin, p_end, make_checked(ptr_, capacity_) + size_);
490  size_ = new_size;
491  }

511 // The number of characters to store in the basic_memory_buffer object itself
512 // to avoid dynamic memory allocation.
513 enum { inline_buffer_size = 500 };
514 
515 /**
516  \rst
517  A dynamically growing memory buffer for trivially copyable/constructible types
518  with the first ``SIZE`` elements stored in the object itself.
519 
520  You can use one of the following type aliases for common character types:
521 
522  +----------------+------------------------------+
523  | Type | Definition |
524  +================+==============================+
525  | memory_buffer | basic_memory_buffer<char> |
526  +----------------+------------------------------+
527  | wmemory_buffer | basic_memory_buffer<wchar_t> |
528  +----------------+------------------------------+
529 
530  **Example**::
531 
532  fmt::memory_buffer out;
533  format_to(out, "The answer is {}.", 42);
534 
535  This will append the following output to the ``out`` object:
536 
537  .. code-block:: none
538 
539  The answer is 42.
540 
541  The output can be converted to an ``std::string`` with ``to_string(out)``.
542  \endrst
543  */
544 template <typename T, std::size_t SIZE = inline_buffer_size, typename Allocator = std::allocator<T>>
545 class basic_memory_buffer : private Allocator, public internal::buffer<T>
546 {
547 private:
548  T store_[SIZE];
549 
550  // Deallocate memory allocated by the buffer.
551  void deallocate()
552  {
553  T *p_data = this->data();
554  if (p_data != store_)
555  Allocator::deallocate(p_data, this->capacity());
556  }
557 
558 protected:
559  void grow(std::size_t size) FMT_OVERRIDE;
560 
561 public:
562  using value_type = T;
563  using const_reference = const T &;
564 
565  explicit basic_memory_buffer(const Allocator &alloc = Allocator()) : Allocator(alloc)
566  {
567  this->set(store_, SIZE);
568  }
569  ~basic_memory_buffer() { deallocate(); }
570 
571 private:
572  // Move data from other to this buffer.
573  void move(basic_memory_buffer &other)
574  {
575  Allocator &this_alloc = *this, &other_alloc = other;
576  this_alloc = std::move(other_alloc);
577  T * data = other.data();
578  std::size_t size = other.size(), capacity = other.capacity();
579  if (data == other.store_) {
580  this->set(store_, capacity);
581  std::uninitialized_copy(other.store_, other.store_ + size,
582  internal::make_checked(store_, capacity));
583  }
584  else {
585  this->set(data, capacity);
586  // Set pointer to the inline array so that delete is not called
587  // when deallocating.
588  other.set(other.store_, 0);
589  }
590  this->resize(size);
591  }
592 
593 public:
594  /**
595  \rst
596  Constructs a :class:`fmt::basic_memory_buffer` object moving the content
597  of the other object to it.
598  \endrst
599  */
600  basic_memory_buffer(basic_memory_buffer &&other) { move(other); }
601 
602  /**
603  \rst
604  Moves the content of the other ``basic_memory_buffer`` object to this one.
605  \endrst
606  */
607  basic_memory_buffer &operator=(basic_memory_buffer &&other)
608  {
609  assert(this != &other);
610  deallocate();
611  move(other);
612  return *this;
613  }
614 
615  // Returns a copy of the allocator associated with this buffer.
616  Allocator get_allocator() const { return *this; }
617 };
618 
619 template <typename T, std::size_t SIZE, typename Allocator>
620 void basic_memory_buffer<T, SIZE, Allocator>::grow(std::size_t p_size)
621 {
622 #ifdef FUZZING_BUILD_MODE_UNSAFE_FOR_PRODUCTION
623  if (p_size > 1000)
624  throw std::runtime_error("fuzz mode - won't grow that much");
625 #endif
626  std::size_t old_capacity = this->capacity();
627  std::size_t new_capacity = old_capacity + old_capacity / 2;
628  if (p_size > new_capacity)
629  new_capacity = p_size;
630  T *old_data = this->data();
631  T *new_data = std::allocator_traits<Allocator>::allocate(*this, new_capacity);
632  // The following code doesn't throw, so the raw pointer above doesn't leak.
633  std::uninitialized_copy(old_data, old_data + this->size(),
634  internal::make_checked(new_data, new_capacity));
635  this->set(new_data, new_capacity);
636  // deallocate must not throw according to the standard, but even if it does,
637  // the buffer already uses the new storage and will deallocate it in
638  // destructor.
639  if (old_data != store_)
640  Allocator::deallocate(old_data, old_capacity);
641 }

698 #ifdef FMT_BUILTIN_CLZLL
699  // Returns the number of decimal digits in n. Leading zeros are not counted
700  // except for n == 0 in which case count_digits returns 1.
701  inline int count_digits(uint64_t n)
702  {
703  // Based on http://graphics.stanford.edu/~seander/bithacks.html#IntegerLog10
704  // and the benchmark https://github.com/localvoid/cxx-benchmark-count-digits.
705  int t = (64 - FMT_BUILTIN_CLZLL(n | 1)) * 1233 >> 12;
706  return t - (n < data::zero_or_powers_of_10_64[t]) + 1;
707  }
708 #else
709  // Fallback version of count_digits used when __builtin_clz is not available.
710  inline int count_digits(uint64_t n)
711  {
712  int count = 1;
713  for (;;) {
714  // Integer division is slow so do it for a group of four digits instead
715  // of for every digit. The idea comes from the talk by Alexandrescu
716  // "Three Optimization Tips for C++". See speed-test for a comparison.
717  if (n < 10)
718  return count;
719  if (n < 100)
720  return count + 1;
721  if (n < 1000)
722  return count + 2;
723  if (n < 10000)
724  return count + 3;
725  n /= 10000u;
726  count += 4;
727  }
728  }
729 #endif
730 
731  // Counts the number of digits in n. BITS = log2(radix).
732  template <unsigned BITS, typename UInt> inline int count_digits(UInt n)
733  {
734  int num_digits = 0;
735  do {
736  ++num_digits;
737  } while ((n >>= BITS) != 0);
738  return num_digits;
739  }

751  // Computes g = floor(log10(n)) and calls h.on<g>(n);
752  template <typename Handler> inline char *lg(uint32_t n, Handler h)
753  {
754  return n < 100
755  ? n < 10 ? h.template on<0>(n) : h.template on<1>(n)
756  : n < 1000000
757  ? n < 10000 ? n < 1000 ? h.template on<2>(n) : h.template on<3>(n)
758  : n < 100000 ? h.template on<4>(n) : h.template on<5>(n)
759  : n < 100000000 ? n < 10000000 ? h.template on<6>(n) : h.template on<7>(n)
760  : n < 1000000000 ? h.template on<8>(n) : h.template on<9>(n);
761  }

763  // An lg handler that formats a decimal number.
764  // Usage: lg(n, decimal_formatter(buffer));
765  class decimal_formatter
766  {
767  private:
768  char *buffer_;
769 
770  void write_pair(unsigned N, uint32_t index)
771  {
772  std::memcpy(buffer_ + N, data::digits + index * 2, 2);
773  }
774 
775  public:
776  explicit decimal_formatter(char *buf) : buffer_(buf) {}
777 
778  template <unsigned N> char *on(uint32_t u)
779  {
780  if (N == 0) {
781  *buffer_ = static_cast<char>(u) + '0';
782  }
783  else if (N == 1) {
784  write_pair(0, u);
785  }
786  else {
787  // The idea of using 4.32 fixed-point numbers is based on
788  // https://github.com/jeaiii/itoa
789  unsigned n = N - 1;
790  unsigned a = n / 5 * n * 53 / 16;
791  uint64_t t = ((1ULL << (32 + a)) / data::zero_or_powers_of_10_32[n] + 1 - n / 9);
792  t = ((t * u) >> a) + n / 5 * 4;
793  write_pair(0, t >> 32);
794  for (unsigned i = 2; i < N; i += 2) {
795  t = 100ULL * static_cast<uint32_t>(t);
796  write_pair(i, t >> 32);
797  }
798  if (N % 2 == 0) {
799  buffer_[N] = static_cast<char>((10ULL * static_cast<uint32_t>(t)) >> 32) + '0';
800  }
801  }
802  return buffer_ += N + 1;
803  }
804  };

835  // Formats a decimal unsigned integer value writing into buffer.
836  // add_thousands_sep is called after writing each char to add a thousands
837  // separator if necessary.
838  template <typename UInt, typename Char, typename F>
839  inline Char *format_decimal(Char *buffer, UInt value, int num_digits, F add_thousands_sep)
840  {
841  FMT_ASSERT(num_digits >= 0, "invalid digit count");
842  buffer += num_digits;
843  Char *end = buffer;
844  while (value >= 100) {
845  // Integer division is slow so do it for a group of two digits instead
846  // of for every digit. The idea comes from the talk by Alexandrescu
847  // "Three Optimization Tips for C++". See speed-test for a comparison.
848  unsigned index = static_cast<unsigned>((value % 100) * 2);
849  value /= 100;
850  *--buffer = static_cast<Char>(data::digits[index + 1]);
851  add_thousands_sep(buffer);
852  *--buffer = static_cast<Char>(data::digits[index]);
853  add_thousands_sep(buffer);
854  }
855  if (value < 10) {
856  *--buffer = static_cast<Char>('0' + value);
857  return end;
858  }
859  unsigned index = static_cast<unsigned>(value * 2);
860  *--buffer = static_cast<Char>(data::digits[index + 1]);
861  add_thousands_sep(buffer);
862  *--buffer = static_cast<Char>(data::digits[index]);
863  return end;
864  }
865 
866  template <typename Char, typename UInt, typename Iterator, typename F>
867  inline Iterator format_decimal(Iterator out, UInt value, int num_digits, F add_thousands_sep)
868  {
869  FMT_ASSERT(num_digits >= 0, "invalid digit count");
870  // Buffer should be large enough to hold all digits (<= digits10 + 1).
871  enum { max_size = std::numeric_limits<UInt>::digits10 + 1 };
872  Char buffer[max_size + max_size / 3];
873  auto end = format_decimal(buffer, value, num_digits, add_thousands_sep);
874  return internal::copy_str<Char>(buffer, end, out);
875  }

877  template <typename Char, typename It, typename UInt>

879  {
880  return format_decimal<Char>(out, value, num_digits, [](Char *) {});
881  }

883  template <unsigned BASE_BITS, typename Char, typename UInt>
884  inline Char *format_uint(Char *buffer, UInt value, int num_digits, bool upper = false)
885  {
886  buffer += num_digits;
887  Char *end = buffer;
888  do {
889  const char *digits = upper ? "0123456789ABCDEF" : data::hex_digits;
890  unsigned digit = (value & ((1 << BASE_BITS) - 1));
891  *--buffer = static_cast<Char>(BASE_BITS < 4 ? static_cast<char>('0' + digit) : digits[digit]);
892  } while ((value >>= BASE_BITS) != 0);
893  return end;
894  }
895 
896  template <unsigned BASE_BITS, typename Char>
897  Char *format_uint(Char *buffer, internal::fallback_uintptr n, int num_digits, bool = false)
898  {
899  auto char_digits = std::numeric_limits<unsigned char>::digits / 4;
900  int start = (num_digits + char_digits - 1) / char_digits - 1;
901  if (int start_digits = num_digits % char_digits) {
902  unsigned value = n.value[start--];
903  buffer = format_uint<BASE_BITS>(buffer, value, start_digits);
904  }
905  for (; start >= 0; --start) {
906  unsigned value = n.value[start];
907  buffer += char_digits;
908  auto p = buffer;
909  for (int i = 0; i < char_digits; ++i) {
910  unsigned digit = (value & ((1 << BASE_BITS) - 1));
911  *--p = static_cast<Char>(data::hex_digits[digit]);
912  value >>= BASE_BITS;
913  }
914  }
915  return buffer;
916  }
917 
918  template <unsigned BASE_BITS, typename Char, typename It, typename UInt>
919  inline It format_uint(It out, UInt value, int num_digits, bool upper = false)
920  {
921  // Buffer should be large enough to hold all digits (digits / BASE_BITS + 1).
922  char buffer[std::numeric_limits<UInt>::digits / BASE_BITS + 1];
923  format_uint<BASE_BITS>(buffer, value, num_digits, upper);
924  return internal::copy_str<Char>(buffer, buffer + num_digits, out);
925  }

1033  // Writes the exponent exp in the form "[+-]d{2,3}" to buffer.
1034  template <typename Char, typename It> It write_exponent(int exp, It it)
1035  {
1036  FMT_ASSERT(-1000 < exp && exp < 1000, "exponent out of range");
1037  if (exp < 0) {
1038  *it++ = static_cast<Char>('-');
1039  exp = -exp;
1040  }
1041  else {
1042  *it++ = static_cast<Char>('+');
1043  }
1044  if (exp >= 100) {
1045  *it++ = static_cast<Char>(static_cast<char>('0' + exp / 100));
1046  exp %= 100;
1047  }
1048  const char *d = data::digits + exp * 2;
1049  *it++ = static_cast<Char>(d[0]);
1050  *it++ = static_cast<Char>(d[1]);
1051  return it;
1052  }

1054  struct gen_digits_params
1055  {
1056  int num_digits;
1057  bool fixed;
1058  bool upper;
1059  bool trailing_zeros;
1060  };
1061 
1062  // The number is given as v = digits * pow(10, exp).
1063  template <typename Char, typename It>
1064  It grisu_prettify(const char *digits, int size, int exp, It it, gen_digits_params params,
1065  Char decimal_point)
1066  {
1067  // pow(10, full_exp - 1) <= v <= pow(10, full_exp).
1068  int full_exp = size + exp;
1069  if (!params.fixed) {
1070  // Insert a decimal point after the first digit and add an exponent.
1071  *it++ = static_cast<Char>(*digits);
1072  if (size > 1)
1073  *it++ = decimal_point;
1074  exp += size - 1;
1075  it = copy_str<Char>(digits + 1, digits + size, it);
1076  if (size < params.num_digits)
1077  it = std::fill_n(it, params.num_digits - size, static_cast<Char>('0'));
1078  *it++ = static_cast<Char>(params.upper ? 'E' : 'e');
1079  return write_exponent<Char>(exp, it);
1080  }
1081  if (size <= full_exp) {
1082  // 1234e7 -> 12340000000[.0+]
1083  it = copy_str<Char>(digits, digits + size, it);
1084  it = std::fill_n(it, full_exp - size, static_cast<Char>('0'));
1085  int num_zeros = (std::max)(params.num_digits - full_exp, 1);
1086  if (params.trailing_zeros) {
1087  *it++ = decimal_point;
1088 #ifdef FUZZING_BUILD_MODE_UNSAFE_FOR_PRODUCTION
1089  if (num_zeros > 1000)
1090  throw std::runtime_error("fuzz mode - avoiding excessive cpu use");
1091 #endif
1092  it = std::fill_n(it, num_zeros, static_cast<Char>('0'));
1093  }
1094  }
1095  else if (full_exp > 0) {
1096  // 1234e-2 -> 12.34[0+]
1097  it = copy_str<Char>(digits, digits + full_exp, it);
1098  if (!params.trailing_zeros) {
1099  // Remove trailing zeros.
1100  while (size > full_exp && digits[size - 1] == '0')
1101  --size;
1102  if (size != full_exp)
1103  *it++ = decimal_point;
1104  return copy_str<Char>(digits + full_exp, digits + size, it);
1105  }
1106  *it++ = decimal_point;
1107  it = copy_str<Char>(digits + full_exp, digits + size, it);
1108  if (params.num_digits > size) {
1109  // Add trailing zeros.
1110  int num_zeros = params.num_digits - size;
1111  it = std::fill_n(it, num_zeros, static_cast<Char>('0'));
1112  }
1113  }
1114  else {
1115  // 1234e-6 -> 0.001234
1116  *it++ = static_cast<Char>('0');
1117  int num_zeros = -full_exp;
1118  if (params.num_digits >= 0 && params.num_digits < num_zeros)
1119  num_zeros = params.num_digits;
1120  if (!params.trailing_zeros)
1121  while (size > 0 && digits[size - 1] == '0')
1122  --size;
1123  if (num_zeros != 0 || size != 0) {
1124  *it++ = decimal_point;
1125  it = std::fill_n(it, num_zeros, static_cast<Char>('0'));
1126  it = copy_str<Char>(digits, digits + size, it);
1127  }
1128  }
1129  return it;
1130  }

1287  template <typename Context> void arg_map<Context>::init(const basic_format_args<Context> &args)
1288  {
1289  if (map_)
1290  return;
1291  map_ = new entry[internal::to_unsigned(args.max_size())];
1292  if (args.is_packed()) {
1293  for (int i = 0;; ++i) {
1294  internal::type arg_type = args.type(i);
1295  if (arg_type == internal::none_type)
1296  return;
1297  if (arg_type == internal::named_arg_type)
1298  push_back(args.values_[i]);
1299  }
1300  }
1301  for (int i = 0, n = args.max_size(); i < n; ++i) {
1302  auto type = args.args_[i].type_;
1303  if (type == internal::named_arg_type)
1304  push_back(args.args_[i].value_);
1305  }

1328  template <typename F> struct padded_int_writer
1329  {

1334  F f;

1348  // Writes an integer in the format
1349  // <left-padding><prefix><numeric-padding><digits><right-padding>
1350  // where <digits> are written by f(it).
1351  template <typename F>
1352  void write_int(int num_digits, string_view prefix, format_specs specs, F f)
1353  {
1354  std::size_t size = prefix.size() + internal::to_unsigned(num_digits);
1355  char_type fill = specs.fill[0];
1356  std::size_t padding = 0;
1357  if (specs.align == align::numeric) {
1358  auto unsiged_width = internal::to_unsigned(specs.width);
1359  if (unsiged_width > size) {
1360  padding = unsiged_width - size;
1361  size = unsiged_width;
1362  }
1363  }
1364  else if (specs.precision > num_digits) {
1365  size = prefix.size() + internal::to_unsigned(specs.precision);
1366  padding = internal::to_unsigned(specs.precision - num_digits);
1367  fill = static_cast<char_type>('0');
1368  }
1369  if (specs.align == align::none)
1370  specs.align = align::right;
1371  write_padded(specs, padded_int_writer<F>{size, prefix, fill, padding, f});
1372  }

1374  // Writes a decimal integer.
1375  template <typename Int> void write_decimal(Int value)
1376  {
1377  auto abs_value = static_cast<uint32_or_64_t<Int>>(value);
1378  bool is_negative = internal::is_negative(value);
1379  if (is_negative)
1380  abs_value = 0 - abs_value;
1381  int num_digits = internal::count_digits(abs_value);
1382  auto &&it = reserve((is_negative ? 1 : 0) + static_cast<size_t>(num_digits));
1383  if (is_negative)
1384  *it++ = static_cast<char_type>('-');
1385  it = internal::format_decimal<char_type>(it, abs_value, num_digits);
1386  }

1488  struct num_writer

1495  {

1651  // Writes a value in the format
1652  // <left-padding><value><right-padding>
1653  // where <value> is written by f(it).
1654  template <typename F> void write_padded(const format_specs &specs, F &&f)
1655  {
1656  // User-perceived width (in code points).
1657  unsigned width = to_unsigned(specs.width);
1658  size_t size = f.size(); // The number of code units.
1659  size_t num_code_points = width != 0 ? f.width() : size;
1660  if (width <= num_code_points)
1661  return f(reserve(size));
1662  auto && it = reserve(width + (size - num_code_points));
1663  char_type fill = specs.fill[0];
1664  std::size_t padding = width - num_code_points;
1665  if (specs.align == align::right) {
1666  it = std::fill_n(it, padding, fill);
1667  f(it);
1668  }
1669  else if (specs.align == align::center) {
1670  std::size_t left_padding = padding / 2;
1671  it = std::fill_n(it, left_padding, fill);
1672  f(it);
1673  it = std::fill_n(it, padding - left_padding, fill);
1674  }
1675  else {
1676  f(it);
1677  it = std::fill_n(it, padding, fill);
1678  }
1679  }

1940  // Parses the range [begin, end) as an unsigned integer. This function assumes
1941  // that the range is non-empty and the first character is a digit.
1942  template <typename Char, typename ErrorHandler>
1943  FMT_CONSTEXPR int parse_nonnegative_int(const Char *&begin, const Char *end, ErrorHandler &&eh)
1944  {
1945  assert(begin != end && '0' <= *begin && *begin <= '9');
1946  if (*begin == '0') {
1947  ++begin;
1948  return 0;
1949  }
1950  unsigned value = 0;
1951  // Convert to unsigned to prevent a warning.
1952  constexpr unsigned max_int = (std::numeric_limits<int>::max)();
1953  unsigned big = max_int / 10;
1954  do {
1955  // Check for overflow.
1956  if (value > big) {
1957  value = max_int + 1;
1958  break;
1959  }
1960  value = value * 10 + unsigned(*begin - '0');
1961  ++begin;
1962  } while (begin != end && '0' <= *begin && *begin <= '9');
1963  if (value > max_int)
1964  eh.on_error("number is too big");
1965  return static_cast<int>(value);
1966  }

2359  template <typename Char, typename IDHandler>
2360  FMT_CONSTEXPR const Char *parse_arg_id(const Char *begin, const Char *end, IDHandler &&handler)
2361  {
2362  assert(begin != end);
2363  Char c = *begin;
2364  if (c == '}' || c == ':')
2365  return handler(), begin;
2366  if (c >= '0' && c <= '9') {
2367  int index = parse_nonnegative_int(begin, end, handler);
2368  if (begin == end || (*begin != '}' && *begin != ':'))
2369  return handler.on_error("invalid format string"), begin;
2370  handler(index);
2371  return begin;
2372  }
2373  if (!is_name_start(c))
2374  return handler.on_error("invalid format string"), begin;
2375  auto it = begin;
2376  do {
2377  ++it;
2378  } while (it != end && (is_name_start(c = *it) || ('0' <= c && c <= '9')));
2379  handler(basic_string_view<Char>(begin, to_unsigned(it - begin)));
2380  return it;
2381  }

2411  // Parses fill and alignment.
2412  template <typename Char, typename Handler>
2413  FMT_CONSTEXPR const Char *parse_align(const Char *begin, const Char *end, Handler &&handler)
2414  {
2415  FMT_ASSERT(begin != end, "");
2416  auto align = align::none;
2417  int i = 0;
2418  if (begin + 1 != end)
2419  ++i;
2420  do {
2421  switch (static_cast<char>(begin[i])) {
2422  case '<': align = align::left; break;
2423  case '>': align = align::right; break;
2424  case '=': align = align::numeric; break;
2425  case '^': align = align::center; break;
2426  }
2427  if (align != align::none) {
2428  if (i > 0) {
2429  auto c = *begin;
2430  if (c == '{')
2431  return handler.on_error("invalid fill character '{'"), begin;
2432  begin += 2;
2433  handler.on_fill(c);
2434  }
2435  else
2436  ++begin;
2437  handler.on_align(align);
2438  break;
2439  }
2440  } while (i-- > 0);
2441  return begin;
2442  }
2443 
2444  template <typename Char, typename Handler>
2445  FMT_CONSTEXPR const Char *parse_width(const Char *begin, const Char *end, Handler &&handler)
2446  {
2447  FMT_ASSERT(begin != end, "");
2448  if ('0' <= *begin && *begin <= '9') {
2449  handler.on_width(parse_nonnegative_int(begin, end, handler));
2450  }
2451  else if (*begin == '{') {
2452  ++begin;
2453  if (begin != end)
2454  begin = parse_arg_id(begin, end, width_adapter<Handler, Char>(handler));
2455  if (begin == end || *begin != '}')
2456  return handler.on_error("invalid format string"), begin;
2457  ++begin;
2458  }
2459  return begin;
2460  }
2461 
2462  template <typename Char, typename Handler>
2463  FMT_CONSTEXPR const Char *parse_precision(const Char *begin, const Char *end, Handler &&handler)
2464  {
2465  ++begin;
2466  auto c = begin != end ? *begin : Char();
2467  if ('0' <= c && c <= '9') {
2468  handler.on_precision(parse_nonnegative_int(begin, end, handler));
2469  }
2470  else if (c == '{') {
2471  ++begin;
2472  if (begin != end) {
2473  begin = parse_arg_id(begin, end, precision_adapter<Handler, Char>(handler));
2474  }
2475  if (begin == end || *begin++ != '}')
2476  return handler.on_error("invalid format string"), begin;
2477  }
2478  else {
2479  return handler.on_error("missing precision specifier"), begin;
2480  }
2481  handler.end_precision();
2482  return begin;
2483  }

2485  // Parses standard format specifiers and sends notifications about parsed
2486  // components to handler.
2487  template <typename Char, typename SpecHandler>
2488  FMT_CONSTEXPR const Char *parse_format_specs(const Char *begin, const Char *end,
2489  SpecHandler &&handler)
2490  {
2491  if (begin == end || *begin == '}')
2492  return begin;
2493 
2494  begin = parse_align(begin, end, handler);
2495  if (begin == end)
2496  return begin;
2497 
2498  // Parse sign.
2499  switch (static_cast<char>(*begin)) {
2500  case '+':
2501  handler.on_plus();
2502  ++begin;
2503  break;
2504  case '-':
2505  handler.on_minus();
2506  ++begin;
2507  break;
2508  case ' ':
2509  handler.on_space();
2510  ++begin;
2511  break;
2512  }
2513  if (begin == end)
2514  return begin;
2515 
2516  if (*begin == '#') {
2517  handler.on_hash();
2518  if (++begin == end)
2519  return begin;
2520  }
2521 
2522  // Parse zero flag.
2523  if (*begin == '0') {
2524  handler.on_zero();
2525  if (++begin == end)
2526  return begin;
2527  }
2528 
2529  begin = parse_width(begin, end, handler);
2530  if (begin == end)
2531  return begin;
2532 
2533  // Parse precision.
2534  if (*begin == '.') {
2535  begin = parse_precision(begin, end, handler);
2536  }
2537 
2538  // Parse type.
2539  if (begin != end && *begin != '}')
2540  handler.on_type(*begin++);
2541  return begin;
2542  }

2544  // Return the result via the out param to workaround gcc bug 77539.
2545  template <bool IS_CONSTEXPR, typename T, typename Ptr = const T *>
2546  FMT_CONSTEXPR bool find(Ptr first, Ptr last, T value, Ptr &out)
2547  {
2548  for (out = first; out != last; ++out) {
2549  if (*out == value)
2550  return true;
2551  }
2552  return false;
2553  }

2556  inline bool find<false, char>(const char *first, const char *last, char value, const char *&out)
2557  {
2558  out = static_cast<const char *>(std::memchr(first, value, internal::to_unsigned(last - first)));
2559  return out != nullptr;

2562  template <typename Handler, typename Char> struct id_adapter
2563  {
2564  FMT_CONSTEXPR void operator()() { handler.on_arg_id(); }
2565  FMT_CONSTEXPR void operator()(int id) { handler.on_arg_id(id); }
2566  FMT_CONSTEXPR void operator()(basic_string_view<Char> id) { handler.on_arg_id(id); }
2567  FMT_CONSTEXPR void on_error(const char *message) { handler.on_error(message); }
2568  Handler & handler;
2569  };

2571  template <bool IS_CONSTEXPR, typename Char, typename Handler>
2572  FMT_CONSTEXPR void parse_format_string(basic_string_view<Char> format_str, Handler &&handler)
2573  {
2574  struct pfs_writer
2575  {
2576  FMT_CONSTEXPR void operator()(const Char *begin, const Char *end)
2577  {
2578  if (begin == end)
2579  return;
2580  for (;;) {
2581  const Char *p = nullptr;
2582  if (!find<IS_CONSTEXPR>(begin, end, '}', p))
2583  return handler_.on_text(begin, end);
2584  ++p;
2585  if (p == end || *p != '}')
2586  return handler_.on_error("unmatched '}' in format string");
2587  handler_.on_text(begin, p);
2588  begin = p + 1;
2589  }
2590  }
2591  Handler &handler_;
2592  } write{handler};
2593  auto begin = format_str.data();
2594  auto end = begin + format_str.size();
2595  while (begin != end) {
2596  // Doing two passes with memchr (one for '{' and another for '}') is up to
2597  // 2.5x faster than the naive one-pass implementation on big format strings.
2598  const Char *p = begin;
2599  if (*begin != '{' && !find<IS_CONSTEXPR>(begin, end, '{', p))
2600  return write(begin, end);
2601  write(begin, p);
2602  ++p;
2603  if (p == end)
2604  return handler.on_error("invalid format string");
2605  if (static_cast<char>(*p) == '}') {
2606  handler.on_arg_id();
2607  handler.on_replacement_field(p);
2608  }
2609  else if (*p == '{') {
2610  handler.on_text(p, p + 1);
2611  }
2612  else {
2613  p = parse_arg_id(p, end, id_adapter<Handler, Char>{handler});
2614  Char c = p != end ? *p : Char();
2615  if (c == '}') {
2616  handler.on_replacement_field(p);
2617  }
2618  else if (c == ':') {
2619  p = handler.on_format_specs(p + 1, end);
2620  if (p == end || *p != '}')
2621  return handler.on_error("unknown format specifier");
2622  }
2623  else {
2624  return handler.on_error("missing '}' in format string");
2625  }
2626  }
2627  begin = p + 1;
2628  }
2629  }

2631  template <typename T, typename ParseContext>
2632  FMT_CONSTEXPR const typename ParseContext::char_type *parse_format_specs(ParseContext &ctx)
2633  {
2634  using char_type = typename ParseContext::char_type;
2635  using context = buffer_context<char_type>;
2636  using mapped_type =
2637  conditional_t<internal::mapped_type_constant<T, context>::value != internal::custom_type,
2638  decltype(arg_mapper<context>().map(std::declval<T>())), T>;
2639  conditional_t<has_formatter<mapped_type, context>::value, formatter<mapped_type, char_type>,
2640  internal::fallback_formatter<T, char_type>>
2641  f;
2642  return f.parse(ctx);
2643  }

2891 template <typename Range>
2892 template <typename T, bool USE_GRISU>
2893 void internal::basic_writer<Range>::write_double(T value, const format_specs &specs)
2894 {
2895  // Check type.
2896  float_spec_handler handler(static_cast<char>(specs.type));
2897  internal::handle_float_type_spec(handler.type, handler);
2898 
2899  char sign = 0;
2900  // Use signbit instead of value < 0 since the latter is always false for NaN.
2901  if (std::signbit(value)) {
2902  sign = '-';
2903  value = -value;
2904  }
2905  else if (specs.sign != sign::none) {
2906  if (specs.sign == sign::plus)
2907  sign = '+';
2908  else if (specs.sign == sign::space)
2909  sign = ' ';
2910  }
2911 
2912  if (!std::isfinite(value)) {
2913  // Format infinity and NaN ourselves because sprintf's output is not
2914  // consistent across platforms.
2915  const char *str =
2916  std::isinf(value) ? (handler.upper ? "INF" : "inf") : (handler.upper ? "NAN" : "nan");
2917  return write_padded(specs, inf_or_nan_writer{sign, handler.as_percentage, str});
2918  }
2919 
2920  if (handler.as_percentage)
2921  value *= 100;
2922 
2923  memory_buffer buffer;
2924  int exp = 0;
2925  int precision = specs.precision >= 0 || !specs.type ? specs.precision : 6;
2926  unsigned options = handler.fixed ? internal::grisu_options::fixed : 0;
2927  bool use_grisu =
2928  USE_GRISU &&
2929  (specs.type != 'a' && specs.type != 'A' && specs.type != 'e' && specs.type != 'E') &&
2930  internal::grisu_format(static_cast<double>(value), buffer, precision, options, exp);
2931  char *decimal_point_pos = nullptr;
2932  if (!use_grisu)
2933  decimal_point_pos = internal::sprintf_format(value, buffer, specs);
2934 
2935  if (handler.as_percentage) {
2936  buffer.push_back('%');
2937  --exp; // Adjust decimal place position.
2938  }
2939  format_specs as = specs;
2940  if (specs.align == align::numeric) {
2941  if (sign) {
2942  auto &&it = reserve(1);
2943  *it++ = static_cast<char_type>(sign);
2944  sign = 0;
2945  if (as.width)
2946  --as.width;
2947  }
2948  as.align = align::right;
2949  }
2950  else if (specs.align == align::none) {
2951  as.align = align::right;
2952  }
2953  char_type decimal_point = handler.use_locale ? internal::decimal_point<char_type>(locale_)
2954  : static_cast<char_type>('.');
2955  if (use_grisu) {
2956  auto params = internal::gen_digits_params();
2957  params.fixed = handler.fixed;
2958  params.num_digits = precision;
2959  params.trailing_zeros = (precision != 0 && (handler.fixed || !specs.type)) || specs.alt;
2960  write_padded(as, grisu_writer(sign, buffer, exp, params, decimal_point));
2961  }
2962  else {
2963  write_padded(as, double_writer{sign, buffer, decimal_point_pos, decimal_point});
2964  }
2965 }

3021 /** Fast integer formatter. */
3022 class format_int
3023 {
3024 private:
3025  // Buffer should be large enough to hold all digits (digits10 + 1),
3026  // a sign and a null character.
3027  enum { buffer_size = std::numeric_limits<unsigned long long>::digits10 + 3 };
3028  mutable char buffer_[buffer_size];
3029  char * str_;
3030 
3031  // Formats value in reverse and returns a pointer to the beginning.
3032  char *format_decimal(unsigned long long value)
3033  {
3034  char *ptr = buffer_ + (buffer_size - 1); // Parens to workaround MSVC bug.
3035  while (value >= 100) {
3036  // Integer division is slow so do it for a group of two digits instead
3037  // of for every digit. The idea comes from the talk by Alexandrescu
3038  // "Three Optimization Tips for C++". See speed-test for a comparison.
3039  unsigned index = static_cast<unsigned>((value % 100) * 2);
3040  value /= 100;
3041  *--ptr = internal::data::digits[index + 1];
3042  *--ptr = internal::data::digits[index];
3043  }
3044  if (value < 10) {
3045  *--ptr = static_cast<char>('0' + value);
3046  return ptr;
3047  }
3048  unsigned index = static_cast<unsigned>(value * 2);
3049  *--ptr = internal::data::digits[index + 1];
3050  *--ptr = internal::data::digits[index];
3051  return ptr;
3052  }
3053 
3054  void format_signed(long long value)
3055  {
3056  unsigned long long abs_value = static_cast<unsigned long long>(value);
3057  bool negative = value < 0;
3058  if (negative)
3059  abs_value = 0 - abs_value;
3060  str_ = format_decimal(abs_value);
3061  if (negative)
3062  *--str_ = '-';
3063  }
3064 
3065 public:
3066  explicit format_int(int value) { format_signed(value); }
3067  explicit format_int(long value) { format_signed(value); }
3068  explicit format_int(long long value) { format_signed(value); }
3069  explicit format_int(unsigned value) : str_(format_decimal(value)) {}
3070  explicit format_int(unsigned long value) : str_(format_decimal(value)) {}
3071  explicit format_int(unsigned long long value) : str_(format_decimal(value)) {}
3072 
3073  /** Returns the number of characters written to the output buffer. */
3074  std::size_t size() const { return internal::to_unsigned(buffer_ - str_ + buffer_size - 1); }
3075 
3076  /**
3077  Returns a pointer to the output buffer content. No terminating null
3078  character is appended.
3079  */
3080  const char *data() const { return str_; }
3081 
3082  /**
3083  Returns a pointer to the output buffer content with terminating null
3084  character appended.
3085  */
3086  const char *c_str() const
3087  {
3088  buffer_[buffer_size - 1] = '\0';
3089  return str_;
3090  }
3091 
3092  /**
3093  \rst
3094  Returns the content of the output buffer as an ``std::string``.
3095  \endrst
3096  */
3097  std::string str() const { return std::string(str_, size()); }
3098 };

3108  // Parses format specifiers stopping either at the end of the range or at the
3109  // terminating '}'.
3110  template <typename ParseContext>
3111  FMT_CONSTEXPR auto parse(ParseContext &ctx) -> decltype(ctx.begin())
3112  {
3113  format_str_ = ctx.begin();
3114  using handler_type = internal::dynamic_specs_handler<ParseContext>;
3115  auto type = internal::type_constant<T, Char>::value;
3116  internal::specs_checker<handler_type> handler(handler_type(specs_, ctx), type);
3117  auto it = parse_format_specs(ctx.begin(), ctx.end(), handler);
3118  auto eh = ctx.error_handler();
3119  switch (type) {
3120  case internal::none_type:
3121  case internal::named_arg_type: FMT_ASSERT(false, "invalid argument type"); break;
3122  case internal::int_type:
3123  case internal::uint_type:
3124  case internal::long_long_type:
3125  case internal::ulong_long_type:
3126  case internal::bool_type:
3127  handle_int_type_spec(specs_.type, internal::int_type_checker<decltype(eh)>(eh));
3128  break;
3129  case internal::char_type:
3130  handle_char_specs(&specs_, internal::char_specs_checker<decltype(eh)>(specs_.type, eh));
3131  break;
3132  case internal::double_type:
3133  case internal::long_double_type:
3134  handle_float_type_spec(specs_.type, internal::float_type_checker<decltype(eh)>(eh));
3135  break;
3136  case internal::cstring_type:
3137  internal::handle_cstring_type_spec(specs_.type,
3138  internal::cstring_type_checker<decltype(eh)>(eh));
3139  break;
3140  case internal::string_type: internal::check_string_type_spec(specs_.type, eh); break;
3141  case internal::pointer_type: internal::check_pointer_type_spec(specs_.type, eh); break;
3142  case internal::custom_type:
3143  // Custom format specifiers should be checked in parse functions of
3144  // formatter specializations.
3145  break;
3146  }

3154  format_str_);
3155  internal::handle_dynamic_spec<internal::precision_checker>(

3209 // A formatter for types known only at run time such as variant alternatives.
3210 //
3211 // Usage:
3212 // using variant = std::variant<int, std::string>;
3213 // template <>
3214 // struct formatter<variant>: dynamic_formatter<> {
3215 // void format(buffer &buf, const variant &v, context &ctx) {
3216 // visit([&](const auto &val) { format(buf, val, ctx); }, v);
3217 // }
3218 // };
3219 template <typename Char = char> class dynamic_formatter
3220 {
3221 private:
3222  struct null_handler : internal::error_handler
3223  {
3224  void on_align(align_t) {}
3225  void on_plus() {}
3226  void on_minus() {}
3227  void on_space() {}
3228  void on_hash() {}
3229  };
3230 
3231 public:
3232  template <typename ParseContext> auto parse(ParseContext &ctx) -> decltype(ctx.begin())
3233  {
3234  format_str_ = ctx.begin();
3235  // Checks are deferred to formatting time when the argument type is known.
3236  internal::dynamic_specs_handler<ParseContext> handler(specs_, ctx);
3237  return parse_format_specs(ctx.begin(), ctx.end(), handler);
3238  }
3239 
3240  template <typename T, typename FormatContext>
3241  auto format(const T &val, FormatContext &ctx) -> decltype(ctx.out())
3242  {
3243  handle_specs(ctx);
3244  internal::specs_checker<null_handler> checker(
3245  null_handler(), internal::mapped_type_constant<T, FormatContext>::value);
3246  checker.on_align(specs_.align);
3247  switch (specs_.sign) {
3248  case sign::none: break;
3249  case sign::plus: checker.on_plus(); break;
3250  case sign::minus: checker.on_minus(); break;
3251  case sign::space: checker.on_space(); break;
3252  }
3253  if (specs_.alt)
3254  checker.on_hash();
3255  if (specs_.precision >= 0)
3256  checker.end_precision();
3257  using range =
3258  internal::output_range<typename FormatContext::iterator, typename FormatContext::char_type>;
3259  visit_format_arg(arg_formatter<range>(ctx, nullptr, &specs_),
3260  internal::make_arg<FormatContext>(val));
3261  return ctx.out();
3262  }
3263 
3264 private:
3265  template <typename Context> void handle_specs(Context &ctx)
3266  {
3267  internal::handle_dynamic_spec<internal::width_checker>(specs_.width, specs_.width_ref, ctx,
3268  format_str_);
3269  internal::handle_dynamic_spec<internal::precision_checker>(
3270  specs_.precision, specs_.precision_ref, ctx, format_str_);
3271  }
3272 
3273  internal::dynamic_format_specs<Char> specs_;
3274  const Char * format_str_;
3275 };

3701  \rst
3702  Constructs a compile-time format string.
3703 
3704  **Example**::
3705 
3706  // A compile-time error because 'd' is an invalid specifier for strings.
3707  std::string s = format(FMT_STRING("{:d}"), "foo");

3709  */
3710 #define FMT_STRING(s) \

3716  FMT_CONSTEXPR operator fmt::basic_string_view<char_type>() const \
3717  { \

3720  } result; \
